l catastrophe; coordinate “natural” questions with sociopolitical ones; and underscore the category of form as a means for generating environmental—and therefore political—knowledge. Moving from the elegy and the industrial novel to the utopian romance, the scientific treatise, and beyond, Ecological Form demonstrates how nineteenth-century thinkers conceptualized the circuits of extraction and violence linking Britain to its global network. Yet the book’s most pressing argument is that this past thought can be a resource for reimagining the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEcocriticism. 0aEcology in literature. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnvironmentalism in literature. 0aIndustrialization in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aAllewaert, Monique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllewaert, Monique.1 aBanerjee, Sukanya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanerjee, Sukanya.1 aGrener, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrener, Adam.1 aHensley, Nathan K.1 aHensley, Nathan K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHensley, Nathan K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKreisel, Deanna K.1 aKreisel, Deanna K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Elizabeth Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Elizabeth Carolyn.1 aMorgan, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Benjamin.1 aOak Taylor, Jesse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOak Taylor, Jesse.1 aPinkus, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca